<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 93 / Lloyd's calls egm vote on new funding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER and BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S OF LONDON is to ask Names at an extraordinary general meeting to
approve plans to introduce new corporate investors to the insurance market.
The meeting, to be held on October 20, is designed to head off any action by
dissident loss-making Names that could delay the entry of new 'incorporated
Names'.
Mr David Rowland, chairman, said in a letter to Names - the individuals
whose assets support the market - that Lloyd's wanted to 'clear the way for
new capital with certainty before the end of October'.
The Lloyd's council - the market's governing body - will consider on
September 8 a rulebook outlining the terms on which corporate capital can
participate in the market. Publication is expected soon afterwards.
The plans to attract corporate investors, announced in April, have caused
considerable controversy at the market. Last week dissident Names failed in
an attempt to force Lloyd's to press new investors to bail out loss-making
Names.
Several investment schemes to bring corporate capital have been developed by
UK and US banks but cannot go ahead until rules are approved.
Mr Rowland also said that Lloyd's had decided on the rules it would follow
if it needed to raise funds in the future through a special levy on members.
A vote by members would be required to approve the levy. Lloyd's said the
voting rights 'should be proportionate to the members' proportionate
capacity' - which would place more voting power in the hands of corporate
investors.
The Association of Lloyd's Members applauded the decision to make an early
decision on voting systems, and said it recognised the severe time pressures
in admitting new capital.
It called for ways to be found for any objections to the new terms for
corporate capital participation to be publicised before the meeting, as
members would be voting without debate on the subject.
</TEXT>
