<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 93 / Industry pay rises at 16-year low, says CBI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PAY RISES in manufacturing industry averaged 2.3 per cent in the second
quarter, the Confederation of British Industry reported yester-day.
It was the lowest quarterly figure recorded by the CBI since its records
began in 1977.
It compares with 2.5 per cent in the first three months of the year and 4
per cent in the second quarter of last year.
Service company pay awards in the second quarter this year provisionally
averaged 2.9 per cent.
The CBI said there was no evidence of a bottoming out in the level of pay
settlements or that workers in companies which imposed pay freezes in
1991-92 were 'catching up', with large rises to compensate for the freezes.
Manufacturers settling during the second quarter reported productivity gains
averaging 3.8 per cent. Although the fall in unit labour costs for the
second quarter is expected to be 2.6 per cent, down from a fall of 3 per
cent in the first quarter, the overall fall is better than Germany, France,
Japan and the US.
Research by the CBI Pay Databank has found that in 1992-93 the average
increase in companies which froze pay in the previous year was 2.1 per cent.
This was lower than the average Databank increase of 3.4 per cent.
The CBI says: 'Therefore there is little evidence to suggest that there has
been a wave of 'catch-up' awards in 1992-93, and the evidence strengthens
the position of public-sector managers facing possible 'catch-up' claims
after the government's 1.5 per cent limit.'
Only 88 Databank companies froze pay for 12 months or more in 1991-92. The
freezes hit non-manual employees more than manual employees, and were
concentrated in the retail and business services sector, although
manufacturing was also affected.
The highest proportion of freezes was in the south-east and the west
Midlands.
Pay freezes of less than 12 months are widespread, affecting about one in
three manufacturers and one in four service-sector companies.
The latest CBI employment affairs report says that, in spite of all the
changes in the law in recent years, the number of employees 'actively taken
out of the collective bargaining net has so far remained relatively low'.
The report says that the decline in union membership and recognition is more
the result of the failure of unions to colonise greenfield sites and small
companies in the services sector.
</TEXT>
