FT  16 AUG 93 / Private plans for child offenders
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is to press ahead with plans to establish private-sector
homes for dangerous children, shrugging off Labour comparisons with the
troubled privatisation of the prison escort service.
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, will publish a consultation paper
today recommending a change in the law to allow private and voluntary
organisations to offer accommodation. Officials said the proposals followed
a rise in the cost of local authority provision of secure accommodation,
which was reserved for children convicted of serious crimes who were too
young to be sent to prison. The average cost of a local authority place is
Pounds 1,680 a week.
Mr David Blunkett, shadow health secretary, said the proposals fell into the
same bracket as the 'farcical' transfer of the prison escort service to
Group 4, which has suffered several embarrassing escapes by prisoners.
'A privatised service can only be profitable if it relies on larger units
that often become colleges of crime,' he said.
Ms Liz Lynne, Liberal Democrat community care spokeswoman, said: 'This is
just another crazy scheme that could end up in catastrophe.'
