<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 93 / University cash crisis highlighted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WIDESPREAD disappointment among applicants for university places after the
publication of A-level results next week will intensify pressure for
universities to be given extra sources of funding.
This follows a record high number of applications and a cut in government
funding - particularly for arts courses - which was not announced until most
universities had already made A-level offers.
Next week the Committee of Vice-Chancellors and Principals will publish a
report on four alternative methods to raise extra funds for higher
education.
These include student loans to be repaid through income tax once students
are employed, or an increase in the level of income tax applicable only to
graduates.
Applications to UK universities as a whole have increased by between 6 per
cent and 7 per cent, while the increase for 'old' universities - those other
than institutions upgraded from polytechnics last year - was 9 per cent.
Yet no funding has been made available to accommodate an increase in
numbers. Instead, the government cut the tuition fees it would pay for each
student in 'classroom-based courses' (excluding laboratory-based and applied
subjects) from Pounds 1,850 to Pounds 1,300.
This decision followed a swift expansion in which the number of students in
higher education increased by 46 per cent over four years. The government is
now aiming for a period of 'consolidation'.
As a result, according to the Universities Central Council on Admissions
(Ucca), tutors will be 'very tight' in vetting applications and many
universities will demand a much more precise match between candidates'
A-level grades and the grade standard expected by the universities.
While all offers of a place must be honoured if the conditions have been
met, there is likely to be no flexibility in dealing with candidates who
narrowly miss their offer, or who achieve the correct grades but not in the
subjects stipulated.
The Polytechnics Central Admissions System (PCAS), which covers the
universities upgraded in the past year, said the tightening followed years
of systematic 'over-recruitment'. It said several institutions had already
announced that no places would be available for classroom-based courses via
the clearing process.
The PCAS attacked the entire admissions system as 'flawed'. Mr Tony Higgins,
chief executive, said conditional offers should be abandoned in favour of a
fairer system in which applicants waited for their A-level results before
applying. University terms would then start in November.
He said: 'Applications should be based on known, not speculative,
attainments.'
</TEXT>
