<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 93 / Companies confident on productivity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COMPETITIVENESS of British industry will continue to improve because of
the impact of high unemployment on wage costs and labour flexibility, a
survey by the 3i venture-capital group says today.
Responses from 1,000 finance directors of the UK's biggest public companies
show them to be overwhelmingly confident that industry will continue to
narrow the productivity gap with the world's most efficient economies, and
that the benefits of last year's devaluation can be sustained.
Respondents cited high unemployment and wider public awareness of the need
to retain competitiveness as explanations for their confidence.
More than two-thirds of the finance directors said the competitive gains of
devaluation would not be whittled away.
Mr John Platt, executive director of 3i, said: 'There is every sign that
1993 will show a rise in productivity higher than any we have seen since the
early 1980s.'
The group's findings follow government figures showing that unit labour
costs are falling, while productivity has reached its highest levels for 6
1/2 years.
Manufacturing wages and salaries per unit of output were 3 per cent lower in
the three months to June than in the same period a year before.
Manufacturing productivity - output per head - was 1.3 per cent higher in
the second quarter compared with the first, and 8.2 per cent higher than in
the same three-month period a year earlier.
Mr Platt said: 'Finance directors view these improvements as a change in the
fundamentals of British industry, not as a short-term windfall resulting
from the recession.'
The directors said a sharper focus on core activities and increased capital
investment had contributed to higher productivity.
