<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 93 / Recovery fails to boost start-ups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ECONOMIC recovery has not yet stimulated growth in the number of
business start-ups, says National Westminster Bank.
The NatWest quarterly start-up index, published today, shows that about
90,000 companies started trading in the second quarter of this year. This
compares with 95,000 in the first three months and 100,000 in the second
quarter of last year.
The total of 185,000 for the first six months of this year is unchanged on
the figure for the second half of last year.
Mrs Jane Bradford, head of NatWest small-business services, said: 'Although
there are signs that recovery in the small-business sector is under way, the
recession has hit small firms hard and, as a result, they are still very
cautious about future prospects.'
She forecast that, if small-business confidence continues to grow, about
370,000 companies would start trading this year. There were 400,000
start-ups last year.
Sole traders made up 60 per cent of start-ups in this year's second quarter,
compared with 50 per cent for the same period in 1987. New businesses took
on an average of four full-time staff, compared with five in 1987's second
quarter.
'Owners are thinking very carefully about the commitments they are prepared
to take on, especially when other people's livelihoods are at risk as well
as their own,' Mrs Bradford said. 'On average they say that they spend
nearly eight months planning their business venture before they actually
start up.'
</TEXT>
