<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 93 / Britain to reappraise evacuations: Airlift of wounded from
Bosnian capital stepped up as 39 adults and children leave
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT and Agencies
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THIRTY-NINE sick or injured adults and children were flown from Sarajevo,
the Bosnian capital, yesterday for treatment in Britain and Sweden. A
further five are expected to be flown out by the Irish government in the
next few days.
Amid claims that the operation had become an emotive publicity stunt, with
insufficient co-ordination among the different aid groups, the British
government yesterday said that it would be 'reassessing' the situation
before it pressed ahead with an offer to send another aircraft to evacuate
civilians.
Officials with the UN High Commissioner for Refugees in the former
Yugoslavia admitted the recent publicity over the evacuations had left them
with more offers of hospital beds than they had patients for.
Nearly 300 beds had been offered for injured Bosnians by European and Moslem
governments, as well as private American groups, although UNHCR officials
had only been wanting to evacuate some 25 victims a week from Sarajevo, it
said.
UN officials stressed more aid was needed across the region, and reiterated
that with funding for its Bosnian operations due to run out in October, the
UNHCR needed more money.
Following the Serb withdrawal from mountains around Sarajevo this weekend
and plans for resumed peace talks in Geneva today, the situation around
Sarajevo was fairly quiet, a spokesman for the UN protection force yesterday
said.
However, fighting was continuing yesterday between Moslem and Croatian
forces in central Bosnia. This was preventing aid convoys from reaching
those regions, he added.
'Things are opening up around Sarajevo. But in central Bosnia things are
still very difficult, although this hasn't had the headlines,' the spokesman
said.
As the diplomatic wrangling over the humanitarian efforts continued, the
British government sought to play down allegations that there was too great
a focus on child victims from Sarajevo, following the emotional press
coverage of Irma Hadzimuratovic, a five-year-old victim of mortar shrapnel
who was evacuated by the British government last week. The 21 patients
evacuated to Britain yesterday would be treated at nine NHS hospitals, with
the cost of the air ambulance being met by the Saudi Arabian royal family,
it added.
Meanwhile, Bosnian Croats threatened to walk out of today's peace talks and
stop aid convoys into central Bosnia unless the international community gave
treatment to their sick and wounded comparable to that received by the
Moslems.
</TEXT>
