<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 93 / Gardening: Eyes have it
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARILYN BENTLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEW PUBLIC gardens can boast that the pleasure of a visit begins in the car
park. But look in any direction from the hilltop field when you arrive at
Mount Ephraim gardens near Faversham, in Kent. You will find none of the
disfigurements of the late 20th century: just woods, orchards and parkland.
Owned by the Dawes family, which has lived there for 300 years, the gardens
owe their layout to enlargements early this century. Begin by walking down
the daisy-strewn slope beside the rock garden. Once overgrown by nettles and
brambles, the area now has flowering shrubs, dwarf conifers, alpines and
bulbs. A great bank of purple sage and a stone Japanese lantern shades the
first of a series of small pools descending towards a small lake.
At the bottom of the water garden is the Japanese Bridge - a photographer's
dream.
Beyond is a pleasant woodland area of mature trees underplanted with
rhododendrons and azaleas. You emerge into meadows rising towards the house.
A series of formal terraces and a tennis court evoke theatrical incarnations
of the English country manor.
Mount Ephraim offers no permanent attractions for children, apart from acres
of space to run around in. Nor are there any bijou shops stocked with pot
pourri, although you can buy the local wine and there is a small craft
centre in the stable block.
Specialists may find the gardens rather short on botanical labelling, but
you would be hard pressed to find anywhere with such a welcoming and
tranquil atmosphere barely 50 miles from London.
Mount Ephraim Gardens, Hernhill, near Faversham, Kent. Open daily until
end-September 11am to 6pm.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
