<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Early bonds rally fails to
inspire Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US STOCKS stayed close to opening values yesterday in spite of more good
inflation news and further gains in bond market prices, writes Patrick
Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 0.56 at 3,569.65,
having moved in a tight trading range all day. The more broadly based
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended up 1.18 at 450.14, while the Amex composite
finished 1.50 firmer at 439.08, and the Nasdaq composite up 1.10 at 718.22.
Trading volume on the NYSE was 215m shares.
After Thursday's profit-taking and program selling, which lopped 14 points
off the Dow, the mood of the markets was much more subdued, with sporadic
buying by bargain hunters the only notable feature.
For the second consecutive day, an early rally in bond prices failed to
inspire equity investors. In late trading the benchmark 30-year government
bond was up  1/4 at 98, and the yield had descended to a record low of 6.346
per cent.
As on the previous day, yesterday's jump in bonds was sparked by good
inflation news.
The Labor department reported that its index of consumer prices rose by just
0.1 per cent in July, a slightly smaller increase than expected. Taken
together with Thursday's reported decline in producer prices, analysts said
that it was clear the inflationary threat to the economy, which reared its
ugly head earlier this year, had fully abated.
Among individual sectors, Mexican stocks were in demand following the news
that trade negotiators from the US, Canada and Mexico had reached an
agreement on labour and environmental issues that had been holding up
approval of the North American Free Trade Agreement.
Telefonos de Mexico rose Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 52 in volume of 3.8m
shares, Mexico Equity &amp; Income Fund climbed Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 18 7/8
and Mexico Fund put on Dollars 1 1/2 at Dollars 26 5/8 .
T2 Medical, down another Dollars 1 1/2 at Dollars 7, continued its plunge in
the wake of news that the company will have to reduce its reported first and
second quarter earnings because of accounting irregularities.
Big computer stocks were in mixed form, with Compaq down Dollars 1 1/2 to
Dollars 52 3/8 , but Hewlett-Packard up Dollars 1 7/8 at Dollars 75 3/8 . On
the Nasdaq market, Borland International fell Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 16 1/4
after a US judge ruled that the company's revised version of its Quattro Pro
product continues to violate Lotus Development's copyrights on its 1-2-3
spreadsheets. Lotus firmed Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 36 1/2 .
Casino Data climbed Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 14 1/4 after the Nevada Gaming
Control Board approved the company's multi-site system to link slot machines
throughout the state.
Canada
TORONTO closed narrowly mixed in relatively quiet trading. The TSE-300
composite index closed up 5.65 points (0.14 per cent) at 4014.62, but
declining issues outnumbered advances 348 to 330. Volume was 47.4m shares,
compared with Thursday's 52.1m. On the week, the 300 composite index rose
about 55 points. Eight of 14 sub-indexes closed higher, led by consumer
products. Real estate was the biggest faller.
</TEXT>
