<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 93 / Revenue contests BES tax relief ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INLAND Revenue is appealing against a High Court judgment that
overturned its decision to deny tax relief to two Pounds 25m business
expansion schemes.
The schemes were issued by National Westminster Bank in conjunction with
Hambros Bank and BZW, the securities arm of Barclays Bank.
The High Court agreed with the banks last month that their loan-back BES
schemes were eligible for tax relief. BES schemes give tax relief to
investors at their highest marginal rate if they hold their investment for
five years.
In his March Budget Mr Norman Lamont, who was then chancellor, abolished
loan-back BES schemes, which allowed investors to withdraw after six months
instead of five years. He ruled that shares in BES companies had to be
issued by the midnight before the Budget if loans were to be made against
them.
The banks had allotted shares but had not listed the shareholdings in the
companies' register of members by the Budget deadline.
In May the Revenue decided that the shares had not been 'issued' and would
not be eligible for tax relief.
But the High Court ruled that the word 'issue' had no fixed meaning and
there was no reason to think that the availability of BES tax relief was
dependent on actual registration of shareholders.
The Revenue said yesterday that it opposed the judgment because it blurred
'the distinction between the issue and allotment of shares, and this could
impinge on other areas of tax legislation'.
</TEXT>
