<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 93 / Mexico promises to increase minimum wage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Carlos Salinas yesterday instructed the labour ministry to raise
Mexico's minimum wage of 13 pesos (Pounds 2.80) a day by national average
productivity increases. He announced the move in a national television
broadcast celebrating the end of negotiations on side agreements to the
North American Free Trade Agreement.
The comments appeared to have been intended as much for the US as Mexico. In
the US Congress, fears that factories will move to Mexico to take advantage
of low Mexican wages have underlined much of the opposition to the trade
pact.
The purchasing power of Mexico's minimum wage has steadily fallen over the
past decade, a result of inflation, low economic growth, and a deliberate
government policy.
However, few Mexicans earn the minimum wage, and the new policy is expected
to have a limited impact. While US officials had heralded President
Salinas's speech an important development, a spokesman for Mr Salinas
categorically denied that any deal had been done with the US administration
over wages. 'There is nothing new in this,' he said.
The broadcast came after Mexico made concessions over the labour and
environmental side agreements, accommodating US demands that the agreements
should have 'teeth'.
The rally in Mexico's stockmarket, which closed 3.8 per cent ahead
yesterday, indicates why the government was willing to make the concessions.
Nafta is expected by investors to boost Mexico's short term economic growth,
accelerate its integration with the industrialised world, and lock in
current economic policies for the foreseeable future.
For these reasons President Salinas has been willing to turn his back on
Mexico's traditional definition of national sovereignty. It is almost
inconceivable that any previous Mexican president would have negotiated
Nafta, let alone willingly submitted Mexico to transnational adjudication in
environmental matters.
Given the lengthy and complicated process involved in punishing violators of
environmental laws, the side agreement on environment is unlikely to have
any immediate impact. Mexico's lack of funds, inexperience in environmental
enforcement, and unwillingness to close factories where under-employment and
poverty exist all mean enforcement in Mexico will probably lag behind that
in the US and Canada for some time.
Mexico made few significant concessions on labour, agreed to share
information with a tri-national commission but not to be bound by any of its
recommendations. The US had been nervous about pressing for a labour
commission with wide powers, for reasons of its own national sovereignty.
</TEXT>
